  <h2>What Are Primitive Reflexes?</h2>
  <p>Primitive reflexes are automatic movements that all infants are born with. They play a crucial role in early survival and development. However, as a child grows older, these reflexes are meant to integrate and fade away. Unfortunately, in some cases, primitive reflexes persist beyond infancy, potentially interfering with higher-level skills. These retained reflexes can contribute to developmental delays and sensory processing difficulties.</p>

  <h2>Why Does It Matter?</h2>
  <p>When primitive reflexes are retained, they can lead to disorganization and imbalances between the left and right sides of the brain. This imbalance may affect various aspects of a child's development.</p>

  <h2>Hemispheric Integration: Bridging the Gap</h2>
  <p>Hemispheric integration refers to the coordination and communication between the two hemispheres of the brain. Each hemisphere controls different functions, and they need to work together harmoniously for optimal functioning. When there's a lack of integration, it can manifest in various ways, including difficulties with attention, learning, and emotional regulation.</p>

  <h2>Our Approach</h2>
  <p>Our therapy activities focus on movement and sensory-based approaches. These activities are designed to stimulate specific areas of the brain, promoting integration and balance. Repetition is key — we work to rewire and reorganize the brain. If you choose to pursue this path, we'll collaborate to create an individualized program tailored to your child's needs and preferences.</p>
  <p>Let's embark on this journey together, supporting your child's growth and development!</p>

